SIMPLE: huff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Huff
<hw>Huff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Huffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Huffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OE. <ets>hoove</ets> to puff
up, blow; prob. of imitative origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To swell;
to enlarge; to puff up; <as>as, <ex>huffed</ex> up with air</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Grew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with insolence and arrogance; to chide or
rebuke with insolence; to hector; to bully.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You must not presume to <qex>huff</qex> us.</q>
<rj><qau>Echard.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Draughts)</fld> <def>To remove from the board (the
piece which could have captured an opposing piece). See <er>Huff</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>, 3.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Huff
<hw>Huff</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To enlarge; to swell
up; <as>as, bread <ex>huffs</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bluster or swell with anger, pride, or arrogance;
to storm; to take offense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This senseless arrogant conceit of theirs made them
<qex>huff</qex> at the doctrine of repentance.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Draughts)</fld> <def>To remove from the board a man
which could have captured a piece but has not done so; -- so called
because it was the habit to blow upon the piece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Huff
<hw>Huff</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A swell of sudden anger or
arrogance; a fit of disappointment and petulance or anger; a rage.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Left the place in a <xex>huff</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>W.
Irving.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A boaster; one swelled with a false opinion of his
own value or importance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lewd, shallow-brained <qex>huffs</qex> make atheism and contempt
of religion the sole badge . . . of wit.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To take huff</b></col>, <cd>to take offence.</cd>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huffcap</ent>⟦br⟧
